AB A central question for firms releasing successive generations of a
   product is whether they should pursue a market-driven approach and align
   own product releases to existing industry-level patterns. While an
   alignment with industry patterns enables firms to capitalize on general
   market receptivity, it may also entail dilution and competitive
   interference effects. Using data on the consumer electronics and
   automotive industries, we show that the effectiveness of such alignment
   depends on two additional timing-related decisions: the firm's release
