AB This manuscript delineates technological innovation into the separate
   dimensions of novelty and meaningfulness to examine how a firm's
   organizational learning modes of adaptive learning and experimental
   learning, together with unabsorbed slack resources, influence the
   effects of novelty and meaningfulness on firm financial performance. The
   multi-method empirical approach leverages secondary data from firm
   patent information and COMPUSTAT, and primary data from senior
   executives at 167 firms in various high-tech industries. The results
   indicate that adaptive learning heightens meaningfulness but diminishes
   novelty, whereas experimental learning harms meaningfulness.
