AB Recent meta-analyses provide clear insights into how service firms can
   benefit from relationship marketing, whereas investigations of
   customers' relational benefits (1) are unclear about the absolute and
   relative strengths by which different relational benefit dimensions
   induce different customer responses and (2) have not simultaneously
   examined the various mediating processes (including perceived value,
   relationship quality, and switching costs) through which relational
   benefits reportedly affect customer loyalty. To consolidate extant
   research on the benefits of relationship marketing for customers, this
   meta-analysis integrates 1242 effect sizes drawn from 235 independent
   samples across 224 papers disseminated in the past two decades. The
   results reveal that all three relational benefits affect loyalty, though
   confidence benefits and social benefits have the strongest effects.
