AB A cancer diagnosis can mark the beginning of one of the most
   resource-demanding experiences and traumatic journeys of one's life.
   Surprisingly, little is known about how consumers assign value, namely
   valorize, in these complex, extraordinary experiences. Using
   sociocultural trauma perspectives and a qualitative study of cancer
   health consumers, we demonstrate that consumers valorize through the
   (re)construction of trauma memories and use three strategies:
   metaphorical framing, flesh-witnessing, and commemorating. These enable
