AB This research investigates the influence that social sources in the
   service environment exert on customer unfriendliness. Drawing on social
   norms theory, the authors demonstrate that descriptive norms (i.e., what
   most people are perceived to be doing in a certain situation), in the
   form of unfriendliness by service employees and fellow customers,
   predicts customers' unfriendliness toward employees. Injunctive norms
   (i.e., beliefs about which behaviors are approved by important others)
   and identification with fellow customers exert moderating effects.
